            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Marcus Petrova arrived in San Francisco in his late twenties, fleeing the stifling heat and limited opportunities of his small Southern hometown. His mother, a tireless single parent who pieced together a living as a home health aide, instilled in him a profound empathy for those struggling. Growing up, Marcus witnessed firsthand the systemic inequities that burdened his community, a formative experience that shaped his life's trajectory. \n\nDriven by a deep desire to effect change, Marcus pursued a bachelor's degree in sociology at a state university, the first in his family to earn a college degree. He then went on to earn a Master's in Social Work from UCBerkeley, his passion for advocacy crystallizing during his fieldwork placements in underserved neighborhoods. The vibrant activism and diverse communities of the Bay Area resonated deeply with him, confirming his decision to make San Francisco his home.\n\nHis career as an LCSW has been dedicated to the \"other services\" spectrum \u2013 often the most complex and challenging cases, working with individuals battling addiction, homelessness, and severe mental health issues. His income, while comfortable, reflects the often-underfunded nature of his vital work. He walks to his office each day, a ritual that grounds him and allows him to observe the city's pulse.\n\nMarcus is a private man, but his quiet strength and unwavering compassion have fostered deep, albeit few, personal connections. He maintains a close relationship with his mother back home and has a chosen family of fellow social workers and community organizers, bound by shared purpose and a dedication to social justice. He\u2019s never married but finds fulfillment in mentoring younger social workers and volunteering at a local soup kitchen on weekends.\n\nAt 54, Marcus dreams of establishing a non-profit focused on providing culturally competent mental health services for Black youth in San Francisco. He believes his experience and network can bridge existing gaps and offer much-needed support. He continues to advocate for policy changes that address the root causes of poverty and inequality.\n\nMarcus lives in a rent-controlled studio apartment in the Mission District, a neighborhood that mirrors the vibrant diversity he cherishes. He feels deeply connected to San Francisco, its imperfect beauty and its persistent fight for a more just world reflecting his own journey. His daily routine is centered around his work and his commitment to others, a testament to the life he has built and the legacy he hopes to leave."
