            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.  The smell of rain-soaked concrete that first day in the Mission, suitcase beside him. A wave of relief washed over Marcus, a stark contrast to the humidity he\u2019d left behind. This city felt different, alive with a complicated energy, a promise of something more. He knew, then and there, he was home. (Age: Late 20s)\n\n2.  Handing a sandwich to a man huddled in a doorway, the raw gratitude in the man's eyes lingered long after Marcus walked away. It was a small act, but it solidified his resolve \u2013 this was the work he was meant to do, finding dignity in the struggle. (Age: Early 30s)\n\n3.  Watching a former client, now sober and housed, speak at a community meeting about their journey. Tears welled in Marcus's eyes. It wasn't his victory alone, but a testament to the power of persistent, often unseen, support. It validated every late night and difficult conversation. (Age: Late 30s)\n\n4.  Sharing late-night burritos and quiet laughter with a fellow organizer after a long day protesting gentrification. These connections, forged in shared passion and mutual understanding, felt like family in a city that could sometimes be isolating. They were his anchors. (Age: 40s)\n\n5.  Presenting his vision for the non-profit to a small group of potential supporters. The nervous energy in his chest was replaced by a surge of purpose. Seeing their nodding heads and genuine interest ignited a fire \u2013 this dream, born from years of witnessing need, felt tangible. (Age: Early 50s)"
